{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἀποκᾰλέω</b>, <br /> <b>recall,</b> especially from exile, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.53, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 1.4.25. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>call away</b> or <b>aside,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “An.” 7.3.35. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>call by a name,</b> especially by way of disparagement, <b>stigmatize as..,</b> τὸν τοῦ μανέντος.. ξύναιμον ἀποκαλοῦντες[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 727; ὀλιγαρχικοὺς καὶ μισοδήμους ἀ. 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 4.16; ὡς ἐν ὀνείδει ἀ. μηχανοποιόν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 512c\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἀργόν, σοφιστὴν ἀ. τινά, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 1.2.57, 1.6.13; οὓς νῦν ὑβρίζει καὶ πτωχοὺς ἀ. 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.211; ὡς ἐν αἰσχρῷ φιλαύτους ἀ. 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1168a30; παράσιτον ἀ. 4th c.BC: Timocles Comicus 19\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χαριεντισμὸν ἀ. <b>call</b> it a <b>sorry</b> jest, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 168d\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; sometimes without any bad sense, τοὺς χαλεπαίνοντας ἀνδρώδεις ἀ.[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1109b18, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “de Equitandi ratione” 10.17, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.776e.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G6438","accentedUnicode":"ἀποκαλέω","shortDef":"to invoke","mediumDef":"to invoke","stepGloss":"to invoke","stepTransliteration":"apokaleō","count":0,"_step_Type":"verb"}]}